ğŸ”¹ Docker Volumes (Persistent Storage)
   Why Use Volumes?
   - Containers are **ephemeral**â€”data is lost when they stop.  
   - Volumes **persist data** (databases, logs, configs).  

Types of Volumes
1. Named Volumes(Managed by Docker)  
   sh
   docker volume create my_volume
   docker run -v my_volume:/data mysql
     

2. Bind Mounts (Host Directory)  
   sh
   docker run -v /host/path:/container/path nginx
   

3. tmpfs Mounts (RAM-only, no disk persistence)  
   sh
   docker run --tmpfs /app/cache redis
   

âœ… Best Practices:
âœ” Use named volumes for databases (`postgres`, `mysql`).  
âœ” Use bind mounts for development (live code reloading).  

